"{\"uid\": \"nbcnews.com-sports-olympics-live-blog-olympic-games-2024-live-updates-rcna162869\", \"text\": \"The Paris Games are underway. You can stream every moment on Peacock.    We have got a full slate ahead of us, with plenty of edge-of-your-seat action in store.  Simone Biles will look to continue her incredible comeback journey by adding more gold to her tally, this time in balance beam and floor exercises. She will be joined on balance beam by fellow American Suni Lee, herself on a comeback journey that almost kept her out of the Games. On floor exercises, another American, Jordan Chiles, will look to challenge for a podium spot.  Here are some other events to look for:  Triathlon  Mixed team relay,2 a.m. ET/8 a.m. Paris  Shooting  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s rapid fire pistol, 3:30 a.m. ET/9:30 a.m. Paris \\u00c2  Mixed team skeet,9 a.m. ET/3 p.m. Paris  Badminton  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s singles, gold medal match, 4:55\\u00c2\\u00a0a.m. ET/10:55 a.m. Paris  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s singles\\u00c2\\u00a0medal matches,8:30 a.m. ET/2:30 p.m. Paris  Gymnastics  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s parallel bars,5:45 a.m. ET/11:45 a.m. Paris  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s balance beam,6:38 a.m. ET/12:38 p.m. Paris  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s high bar,7:33 a.m. ET/1:33 p.m. Paris  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s floor exercise,8:23 a.m. ET/2:23 p.m. Paris  Canoe Slalom\\u00c2  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s kayak cross, 10:55 a.m. ET/4:55 p.m. Paris  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s kayak cross, 11 a.m. ET/5 p.m. Paris  Track and Field\\u00c2  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s pole vault, 1 p.m. ET/7 p.m. Paris  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s discus,2:30 p.m. ET/8:30 p.m. Paris  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 5000m,3:15\\u00c2\\u00a0p.m. ET/9:15 p.m. Paris  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 800m,3:47 p.m. ET/9:47 p.m. Paris  Cycling\\u00c2  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s team sprint medal rounds,1:54 p.m. ET/7:54 p.m. Paris\\u00c2\\u00a0\\u00c2  Basketball\\u00c2  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 3x3 tournament medal games,3 p.m. ET/9 p.m. Paris\\u00c2  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 3x3 tournament medal games,3:30\\u00c2\\u00a0p.m. ET/9:30\\u00c2\\u00a0p.m. Paris  Surfing\\u00c2  Men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s medal matches,3:24\\u00c2\\u00a0p.m. ET/9:24 p.m. Paris  Women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s medal matches,4:05\\u00c2\\u00a0p.m. ET/10:05 p.m. Paris  Team USA added five\\u00c2gold medals,\\u00c2two silver medals and three bronze medals to its tally at the Paris Games today, bringing its total medal count to 71.  The five golds were in track and field, golf, road cycling and swimming; the two silvers were in archery and swimming; and the three bronze were in gymnastics, track and field and skeet shooting.  Twenty medals were handed out today, and the U.S. added half of those to its count.  It is top among competing nations and groups andtied for the most gold medalswith China at 19. The Americans have 19 gold, 26 silver and 26 bronze medals.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Olympic swimmer Katie Ledecky just made history as the most decorated U.S. female Olympic athlete, with 14 medals. She sat down with NBC News\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 Lester Holt to talk about how her latest victories felt and what she hopes to do next.  Ethan Katzberg won Canada\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s first gold in hammer throw today.  Katzberg\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s medal is the first of any color in the event since 1912, when Duncan Gillis won silver. This is the third straight Games where Canada has won at least one track and field gold medal after having gone four consecutive Games without one.  Hungary\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Bence Hal\\u00c3\\u00a1sz won silver, and Ukraine\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Mykhaylo Kokhan won bronze.  Hal\\u00c3\\u00a1sz continues a tradition: Hungary has had six track and field medals in the last 50 years, all of which have been in throwing events.  Meanwhile, this is Ukraine\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s second medal ever in this event, men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s or women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s. The first medal went to Oleksandr Krykun, who won silver in 1996.  Ukraine won three track and field medals today after having won only one track and field medal in each of the last two Olympics.  American Rudy Winkler placed sixth in the final, and fellow American Daniel Haugh was eliminated in qualifying.  A\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ja Wilson led a balanced offensive effort while some ferocious defense helped propel the U.S. to a convincing win over Germany to conclude group play.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Eight men \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 the entire starting field \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 in the 100 meters today finished in under 10 seconds, a historic first for a wind-legal race, according toWorld Athletics, the governing body for athletics, including track and field.  The race was so tight that the gold medalist, Team USA's Noah Lyles, and the silver medalist, Jamaica's Kishane Thompson, both posted times of 9.79, with Lyles winning the battle of decimal places by 0.005 seconds.  Today's last-place finisher, Jamaica's Oblique Seville, posted a 9.91, which would have been good enough for fourth place at the 2020 Tokyo Olympics,according toOlympicrecords.  Six finalists in Tokyo finished in under 10 seconds, with one runner disqualified and one posting a \\\"did not finish.\\\"  A composite image of the eight men competing in the 100-meter final on Sunday at the Paris Olympics.\\u00c2Hector Vivas / Getty Images  The photo finish in the men's 100-meter final at the Paris Olympic Games.\\u00c2World Athletics  Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Noah Lyles took the gold in\\u00c2\\u00a0the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 100-meter final at the Paris Olympics \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094\\u00c2\\u00a0by five thousandths of a second.  Lyles, who won today with a time of 9.784 seconds, came out just barely ahead of Jamaica\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Kishane Thompson (who ran in 9.789) and USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Fred Kerley (whose time was 9.81).  The race was so close that even the commentators nearly called the wrong winner before the\\u00c2photo finish, which showed Lyles being the first to lean over the finish line even as others managed to step over it before him.  Read the full story here.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Bold American sprinting star Noah Lyles arrived at the Paris Olympics announcing his intentions of leaving with four gold medals.  One down, three to go.  The 27-year-old from Virginia\\u00c2won his first gold medal\\u00c2today by bolting to the 100-meter title in a personal best 9.79 seconds in front of a deafening, sold-out Stade de France crowd.  A self-described showman who thrives on a large audience, Lyles ran from behind for much of the first 90 meters while chasing down Jamaica\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Kishane Thompson to a photo finish. The sprinters waited nervously at the finish line, watching the scoreboard for results.  Lyles froze when it showed he had prevailed by one of the narrowest margins \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 five-thousandths of a second.  Read the full story here.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Americans Gerek Meinhardt, Alexander Massialas, Nick Itkin and Miles Chamley-Watson took on France in the bronze match of the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s team foil event. France won 45-32 over the two-time defending bronze medalists.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Snoop Dogg and Martha Stewart took in equestrian competition today, with the rapper showing fascination with the traditions of the sport as it returned to its Olympics birthplace in Paris.  \\\"Only in TV and movies have I seen things of this nature,\\\" Snoop, in formal dressage attire, said as he strolled equestrian grounds with Stewart.  The pair took in the grace and fancy footwork of dressage as English rider Becky Moody wowed spectators with her performance atop horse Jagerbomb.  Teammate Charlotte Fry used Queen's \\\"Another One Bites the Dust\\\" for her performance as Snoop and Stewart watched from a studio. The U.K. equestrian team earned bronze in dressage.  Stewart said she has reserved a stall for Snoop at her stable when he's ready to get a horse. Snoop said the time in Paris is helping him get over a fear of horses.  \\\"This is one of my new favorite sports,\\\" he said.  U.S. duo Kelly Cheng and Sara Hughes punched their ticket to the Olympic beach volleyball quarterfinals, gutting out a gritty win against Italy\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Marta Menegatti and Valentina Gottardi in the Round of 16.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Jessica Fox\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s quest for a third gold medal at the 2024 Paris Olympics was denied by her own sister in the heats of kayak cross.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Algerian boxer Imane Kheliftook to social mediato congratulate gymnast Kaylia Nemour for hergold medal winin today's uneven bars final.  It's the first Olympic gymnastics medal for any African nation. Both Nemour and Khelif have dealt with obstacles outside the field of play on their journeys to the Olympic podium.  Nemour previously represented France but obtained Algerian citizenship through her paternal ancestry after her home federation tried to bar her from competing. Khelif's gender identitycame under disputeat these Games, but she the IOC cleared her to compete.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI want to tell the entire world that I am a female, and I will remain a female,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Khelif said yesterday afterwinning a matchthat would guarantee her a medal in Paris.  PARIS \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094\\u00c2Suni Lee held down the fort\\u00c2\\u00a0as the only American in today\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s uneven bars final, earning a bronze and successfully defending her podium finish in Tokyo.  Algeria\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Kaylia Nemour fulfilled her long-awaited destiny by winning gold. Qiu Qiyuan of China took silver.  Lee had the advantage of going last, which gave her the opportunity to perform the most strategic routine possible. She earned a 14.800 with a slightly more conservative routine and became the first U.S. woman to win two Olympic medals in the event.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Read the full story here.  Jimmer Fredette of the U.S. during a men's 3x3 basketball pool round game against France on Friday.\\u00c2Lintao Zhang / Getty Images  PARIS \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 Former\\u00c2college hoops star\\u00c2\\u00a0and NBA veteran Jimmer Fredette tore ligaments playing for Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 3x3 Olympics team and will be sidelined for about six months, he revealed late today on social media.  The Americans didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t get out of group play and suffered a tournament-ending\\u00c221-6 loss to the Netherlands, landing\\u00c2them\\u00c2\\u00a0in seventh place\\u00c2among eight squads.  Fredette said he tore two ligaments in his adductor in his second game in Paris, a loss to Poland. He was on the bench in uniform but didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t play the rest of the way.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThis is devastating for me as I have put two years into qualifying for the Olympics with this group who are my brothers,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Fredette said in a statement on Instagram.  Read the full story here.  The last heat in the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 1,500 meters saw defending Olympic gold medalist Jakob Ingebrigtsen and reigning world champion Josh Kerr face off.  Ingebrigtsen won the heat with a time of 3:32.38, 0.08 faster than Kerr.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Americans Yared Nuguse and Hobbs Kessler finished 1-2 in their 1,500-meter semifinal.  They finished with the top two times of 3:31.72 and 3:31.97, respectively. They will face favorites Ingebrigtsen and Kerr tomorrow.  We apologize, this video has expired.  World record holder Yaroslava Mahuchikh of Ukraine won her first Olympic gold medal in the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s high jump, edging Australia\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Nicola Olyslagers, who claimed silver for the second consecutive Olympics.  We apologize, this video has expired.  American Juliette Whittaker posted a time of 1:57.76 in the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 800-meter semifinal to advance to the final in Paris.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Quarterfinal matchups in women's water polo are set, with the U.S. meeting Hungary on Tuesday.  The game is scheduled to start at 2:35 p.m. ET. The other quarterfinal matchups, all scheduled for Tuesday, are Canada vs. Spain (8 a.m. ET), the Netherlands vs. Italy (9:35 a.m. ET) and Australia vs. Greece (1 p.m. ET).  Semifinals are scheduled for Thursday. Medal matches, including the final, are expected to take place Saturday.  The U.S. and Spain have been the gold medal favorites, and a possible matchup in the final would reprise the 2020 Tokyo Olympics, where the Americans took gold.  Spain beat the women's team in early pool play in Paris 13-11, but the U.S. team, hoping for an unprecedented fourth consecutive gold medal in Olympics water polo, men's or women's, has a greater goal differential \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 26 compared to Spain's 15.  Scottie Scheffler joined Mike Tirico to talk about winning gold in the Olympic men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s golf event and what it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s like to compete in the Games.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Just one day after winning an historic gold medal for the Philippines on the floor exercise, Carlos Yulo picked up a second gold medal on the vault.  We apologize, this video has expired.  NANTERRE, France \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 Bobby Finke and the U.S. women set world records in the 1,500-meter freestyle and\\u00c2\\u00a0the 4x100-meter medley today, adding final touches of glory for Americans, who suffered a relative collapse in the gold market but still took home the most medals from this quadrennial swim meet.  Gold medalist Bobby Finke of the U.S. poses after the men's 1500m freestyle Sunday.\\u00c2Jonathan Nackstrand / AFP - Getty Images  The U.S. made\\u00c228 visits to the Paris La D\\u00c3\\u00a9fense Arena podium, but Americans were on the top step only eight times.  While both numbers were more than any other country's, it was a slight step back by supremely high U.S. standards.  Read the full story here.  U.S. cyclist Kristen Faulkner surprised everyone when she won the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s road race with a time of 3:49:23. Marianne Vos of the Netherlands edged out Lotte Kopecky of Belgium for silver. Chlo\\u00c3\\u00a9 Dygert\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s crash affected the race.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Team USA picked up 18 medals yesterday \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 five gold, six silver, seven bronze \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094the most for the U.S. in a single day since Oct. 1, 1988, at the Seoul Games, when the U.S. also won 18.  Entering these Games, only five athletes in Olympic history had ever won four gold medals in the same individual event. Yesterday, two American athletes joined that list in a matter of hours.  Vincent Hancock became the sixth athlete to complete the feat, winning his fourth gold medal in shooting\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s skeet.\\u00c2\\u00a0Later, swimmer Katie Ledecky won her fourth gold medal in the women's 800-meter freestyle.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Full prime-time coverage begins tonight on NBC and Peacock at 7 p.m. ET.  Noah Lyles won the men's 100 meters by five-thousandths of a second over Jamaica's Kishane Thompson \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094\\u00c2Lyles' torso crossing the line first.  Here's the photo finish.  The photo finish in the men's 100-meter final.\\u00c2World Athletics  According to official race data, Noah Lyles had the worst reaction time of the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 100-meter final, as he was in last place for the first 40 meters and still in seventh at the halfway point.  In fact, he never led the race until the final few steps, pipping by the smallest of margins Kishane Thompson, who was winning for much of the sprint, according to the data.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cOh shhh ...!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Lyles exclaimed, just stopping himself short, when reporters told him about his improbable midrace comeback.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSlowest reaction time? Dang, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m amazing. That\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s crazy! That\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s crazy! That just goes to prove that reaction time does not win races.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Noah Lyles said he thought Jamaica\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Kishane Thompson\\u00c2\\u00a0had won the 100-meter final when the pair crossed the line five-thousandths of a second apart.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI did think Thompson had it at the end,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Lyle told a scrum of reporters. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI went up to him afterward, while we were waiting. I even said, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Bro I think you got that one, big dog.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 And and then my name popped up and I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m like, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Oh, my gosh, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m amazing!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he added with a laugh.  When his name did show up on the giant screen in the stadium, Lyles said, it came as a rare surprise for a man never short of self-confidence.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m going to be honest, I wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t ready to see it,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAnd that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the first time I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve ever said that in my head that I wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t ready to see it.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Thompson \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cwas a few quite a few lanes over \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in lane four, I was in lane seven \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 so it was hard for me to picture where we were. But I guess that was a good thing.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Crazy but true: Kenny Bednarek\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s time of 9.88 in the 100-meter sprint would have earned him a medal at the Rio or Tokyo Games.  In Paris, he ended up in seventh.  After losing the 100-meter gold to Noah Lyles by five-thousandths of a second, Jamaica's Kishane Thompson said Lyles went up to him after the race and said he thought that Thompson had won it.  Thompson, on the other hand, did not have a clue until the results were officially announced.  \\\"I could not see him. ... He was to my far right, so I wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t sure,\\\" Thompson told reporters. \\\"My closest race ever.\\\"  Asked whether he thought runners should share the gold medal, Thompson quickly dismissed the idea, asserting that the sport was too competitive for such a thing.  Thompson, 23, had run faster times than Lyles this season, including in the Olympic heats leading up to the final. He said he would have loved to win the gold but still felt \\\"super grateful\\\" for the silver at his first Olympics.  After fulfilling part one of his Olympic destiny, Noah Lyles said that for him, there was never any doubt.  \\\"I was always the fastest man in the world,\\\" he said after his 100-meter win. \\\"Now I just got the medals to prove it.\\\"  Asked whether he has ever run like that before, he said he has \\\"had many races like that, but never at the Olympics.\\\"  \\\"I will tell you that, that was an amazing moment, but it was tight, and it was great,\\\" he said.  Noah Lyles claimed the 100 meters in one of the tightest finishes in history. Here's an overhead shot of the finish.  Lyles could be the first sprinter to win the Olympic double since Usain Bolt in 2016 and the first American since Carl Lewis in 1984.  The most difficult test, the 100 meters, is complete, but Thursday he will also have to win the 200-meter final, which is his signature event. Lyles achieved the elusive feat at last year's world championships.  He could win a third Olympic gold medal when he runs the 4x100-meter relay Thursday.  Amid an insanely talented crop of runners, all three Americans running the 1500-meter race will vie for gold in the final.  American record holder Yared Nuguse was the fastest in the two semifinal heats, clocking in at 3:31.72, with fellow American Hobbs Kessler right behind him.  Finishing first in the other heat was defending Olympic champion Jakob Ingebrigtsen from Norway, followed by defending world champion Josh Kerr from Great Britain, and USA's Cole Hocker in third.  Nuguse, Kessler and Hocker each won a medal at World Indoors in March and will look for their first Olympic medals in what promises to be an exhilarating final on Tuesday.  A moment of outrageous drama here at the Stade de France. First a dazzling light show that illumined the arena in a constellation of purple. Then the athletes came out, with eventual winner Noah Lyles running and jumping down the track to ostentatiously announce his presence.  Then from sheer noise to pin-drop quiet as the runners lined up on the start.  After the starting gun, from the stands it was hard to pick a clear favorite during the sub-10 seconds they were haring down the track. Spectators and competitors alike seemed none the wiser as to who had won, with Lyles only celebrating when the photo finish was declared.  By just five thousandths of a second, Noah Lyles ended a 20-year American gold medal drought in the men's 100-meter sprint.  After a tense review period, Lyles earned his first Olympic gold medal. He's halfway to his goal of winning the Olympic double, which will come down to the 200-meter Thursday.  Upon clinching the gold, he looked straight into the camera and said, \\\"America, I told you.\\\"  Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s\\u00c2\\u00a0Noah Lyles wins gold in the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 100-meter final and Fred Kerley gets bronze!  After fleeing her hometownon the front lines of Russia\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s invasion, Ukrainian high jumper Yaroslava Mahuchikh has just won gold at the Stade de France.  An almighty roar erupted from the stands when it became clear that Mahuchikh had bested her main rival, Australia\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Nicola Olyslagers. So did it too when she rang the Olympic champions bell inside the stadium, which will be hung inside the rebuilt Notre-Dame Cathedral after the Games.  Aside from her remarkable origin story, Mahuchikh has captured the attention this tournament for her unique routine in between jumps: She swaddles herself in a sleeping bag. Olyslagers, meanwhile, furiously writes in her journal.  After an epic gold-medal battle, the pair embraced as soon as the result was confirmed.  After the U.S. women took gold in the team foil event, the men narrowly missed the podium in theirs, losing to France 45-32.  Following strong bouts in the first two relays from USA's Alexander Massialas and individual bronze medalist Nick Itkin, the French fencers dominated the remaining seven, picking up momentum from the energized home crowd and securing the bronze medal.  In the fencing finale of this Olympic Games, Italy and Japan are currently fighting in a tight match for gold.  Scottie Scheffler, Tommy Fleetwood and Hideki Matsuyama accept their medals after the conclusion of the Olympic men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s golf event.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Team USA's Nia Akins finished third in her semifinal for the women's 800-meter, but her time of 1:58.20 means she wasn't quick enough to qualify for the final. However, that does mean that her compatriot Juliette Whittaker does go through, with her time of 1:57.76 being enough to make tomorrow night's denouement.  Juliette Whittaker of Team USA gave an extraordinary push on the back straight to finish third in her women's 800-meter semifinal. Only the top two go through automatically, so Whittaker will have to wait until the last round to see if she makes the cut.  While Team USA dominates the 5x5 men's basketball pool, the 3x3 team has struggled, finishing 2 for 5 in the pool rounds and ultimately failing to advance.  After losing its first four games, the 3x3 men's team came back to win their next two, giving themselves a chance to win a third and advance to the play-in rounds. But the Netherlands dashed those hopes quickly with a commanding 21-6 win today.  The U.S. team had been playing shorthanded since losing key player Jimmer Fredette to a leg injury in their second game.  Meanwhile, the women's 3x3 team will look to defend their gold medal from Tokyo and face Spain in the semifinals tomorrow.  With all the heats done, we now know that Kenny Bednarek has qualified for the men's 100-meter final despite not finishing in the top two of his heat. Bednarek and Olympic champion Lamont Marcell Jacobs, of Italy, had the two fastest times of those who did not automatically go through.  That means that three of the eight finalists will be Americans: Bednarek, Noah Lyles and Fred Kerley, who qualified automatically in the other heats.  Jon Rahm was four shots clear of the field on the back nine Sunday at the Olympic men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s event, but finished without a medal. He tried to put his emotions into words.  We apologize, this video has expired.  Team USA's Fred Kerley finished second in his semifinal of the men's 100-meter sprint, meaning he joins fellow countryman Noah Lyle in the final.  In the second semifinal for the men's 100-meter sprint, Team USA's Kenny Bednarek has come in fourth, meaning he will have to hope he is among the fastest also-rans if he has any hope of qualifying for the final.  Only the top two go through from each heat, plus the next fastest two runners.  Even after winning gold in Tokyo, Chinese Taipei duo Yang Lee and Chi-lin Wang were not the favorites to win men's badminton doubles in Paris. China's Wei Keng Liang and Chang Wang loomed large as the No. 1-ranked pair in the world after winning the Asian Championships earlier this year.  But Lee and Wang prevailed, winning an extremely close, emotionally charged three-game match against their Chinese opponents, and clinching their second straight gold medal in the event. Overcome with emotion, Lee and Wang collapsed to the ground as their supporters erupted into a standing ovation.  We apologize, this video has expired.  American sprinter Noah Lyles bagged a comfortable second place in the men's 100-meter semifinal, earning him a place in the final later this evening. It was a photo finish for first place with Jamaica's Oblique Seville, who won the race, but neither man's place in the final looked in doubt.  It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a beautiful evening at the Stade de France, where crowds are arriving for an evening session of athletics capped by the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 100-meter final.  Golden sunshine, high cirrus clouds and a pleasant 77 degrees are a recipe for good vibes at the Olympic Stadium north of Paris.  On the road to the arena, food trucks selling 10-euro pints of \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cbi\\u00c3\\u00a8re blonde\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d are circumventingthe Games\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 abstemious no-booze policy, and seemingly every nation\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s colors can be seen among the masses traipsing the 15 minutes from the Metro to the bleachers.  American women set a world record in the 4x100-meter medley, pulling away to win the final swimming race of the Paris Olympics.  The time of 3:49.62 topped silver Australia and bronze China.  The race broke the tie for gold medals between the U.S. and Australia. Both nations entered the final race with seven gold medals in swimming in Paris before the Americans emerged victorious.  PARIS \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 Belgium\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Olympic committee announced Sunday that it would withdraw its team from the mixed relay triathlon at the Paris Olympics after one of its competitors who swam\\u00c2in the Seine River\\u00c2\\u00a0fell ill.  Claire Michel, who competed\\u00c2in the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s triathlon Wednesday,\\u00c2\\u00a0\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cis unfortunately ill and will have to withdraw from the competition,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d the Belgian Olympic and Interfederal Committee said in a statement.  The mixed relay triathlon is scheduled for Monday, with the swim portion of the competition slated for the Seine as well. The statement did not elaborate on Michel\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s illness but it comes after concerns over the\\u00c2river\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s water quality.  Nigeria made history earlier today as the first African team, men's or women's, to reach the Olympic basketball quarterfinals.  We apologize, this video has expired.  The 12th-ranked Nigerians won 79-70 over fifth-ranked Canada, fueled by a game-high 21 points from Ezinne Kalu. Canada was left winless in three games and eliminated.  Pan Zhanle anchored China to a thrilling come-from-behind win in the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s swimming 4x100 medley relay, rallying past the United States and France.  The U.S. and hosts were neck and neck headed into the freestyle before Pan\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s time of 45.92 put his team past American Hunter Armstrong (47.19) and Frenchman\\u00c2\\u00a0Florent Manaudou (47.59).  The 4x100 medley is considered one of America\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s strongest\\u00c2\\u00a0events, with the U.S. having captured gold in 15 of 16 Olympic finals before tonight.  American Bobby Finkedefended his 1500-meter freestyle titlein word-record fashion, winning a second consecutive gold in the arduous race.\\u00c2  The Tampa native pulled away from Italy\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Gregorio Paltrinieri in the final 50 and touched the wall at 14:30.67, besting the previous mark held by China\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Sun Wang, who had a time of 14:31.02 in 2012.  Ireland\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Daniel Wiffen, considered the favorite here, took bronze.  Despite an impressive first two games in its first-ever Olympics, the German women's basketball team could not come close to breaking the U.S. women's formidable winning streak, as the U.S. cruised to an 87-68 victory.  A'ja Wilson and Breanna Stewart each scored in the double digits, but the star of the game was Jackie 